Won't that hurt him,
all that oil and metal?

221
00:12:14,219 --> 00:12:18,178
He may slide out of bed tonight
and end up pointing at the North Pole.

222
00:12:18,257 --> 00:12:20,623
- You mean like a magnet?
- If he gets real bad...

223
00:12:20,693 --> 00:12:24,151
we'll stick him to the side of a boxcar
and send him down to Seoul.

224
00:12:24,229 --> 00:12:28,393
Oh, you better tell the boys playing horseshoes
to hold up when Klinger walks by.

225
00:12:28,467 --> 00:12:31,732
Soldier, your repairs are over.
We're trading you in on a domestic model.

226
00:12:31,804 --> 00:12:34,830
- Should we turn back his speedometer?
- Against the Geneva Convention.

227
00:12:34,907 --> 00:12:36,875
- You...
- Uh-huh.

228
00:12:36,942 --> 00:12:39,433
- Head.
- Little tight around the crotch?

229
00:12:39,511 --> 00:12:42,947
Soo Ling say, "Thank you."

230
00:12:43,015 --> 00:12:46,212
- Captain Hawkeye Pierce
say, "You're welcome."
- <i>[Klinger Moaning]</i>

231
00:12:47,252 --> 00:12:49,482
- Klinger, what is it?
- Something I ate.

232
00:12:49,555 --> 00:12:52,490
I told you the food here
should not be taken internally.

233
00:12:52,558 --> 00:12:54,526
I had a couple of bolts,
a horn button...

234
00:12:54,593 --> 00:12:56,561
part of a windshield wiper
and a condenser.

235
00:12:56,628 --> 00:12:59,096
- Well-balanced meal.
- But crazy.

236
00:12:59,164 --> 00:13:01,257
- Not crazy enough. [Moans]
- I get it.

237
00:13:01,333 --> 00:13:04,666
Baker! X-ray the Lebanese for hardware.
He's in for a tune-up.

238
00:13:04,737 --> 00:13:07,365
<i>[Hawkeye]</i>
<i>And try not to rattle when you walk.</i>

239
00:13:08,874 --> 00:13:10,865
Sir, this message
just come in for you.

240
00:13:10,943 --> 00:13:13,275
It's from your friend Lieutenant Brooks.
He's on his way.

241
00:13:13,345 --> 00:13:16,007
- On his way?
- Yeah. He's coming here.

242
00:13:16,081 --> 00:13:19,016
- He heard about the emergency.
He's bringing an admiral.
- An admiral?

243
00:13:19,084 --> 00:13:21,848
- Radar, there's no emergency.
- There isn't?

244
00:13:21,920 --> 00:13:24,115
- No.
- No. We were working on a crossword puzzle.

245
00:13:24,189 --> 00:13:27,352
- We needed a word. Don't you remember?
- Ooh, that's right.

246
00:13:27,426 --> 00:13:31,226
But, hey, Lieutenant Brooks is coming here,
and so's the admiral.

247
00:13:31,296 --> 00:13:33,560
Boy, you guys
are in a lot of trouble.

248
00:13:35,868 --> 00:13:37,836
Nice.

249
00:13:52,017 --> 00:13:54,542
- Sirs?
- Where can I find Dr. Pierce, Corporal?

250
00:13:54,620 --> 00:13:57,680
Uh, that tent right over there, sir...
smells like dirty socks.

251
00:13:57,756 --> 00:14:00,691
That jeep was a kidney buster.
Soldier, the head?

252
00:14:00,759 --> 00:14:02,693
Oh, I'm sorry, sir.

253
00:14:02,761 --> 00:14:06,219
- Latrine.
- Oh, it's right over there.

254
00:14:06,298 --> 00:14:08,994
- Thank you.
- Welcome.

255
00:14:09,067 --> 00:14:11,160
Third hole pinches!

256
00:14:11,236 --> 00:14:13,796
- Medicine's come a long way, Beej.
- Mmm.

257
00:14:13,872 --> 00:14:16,238
There was a time when
proctologists used candles.

258
00:14:16,308 --> 00:14:18,538
O-O-Oh, that smarts!

259
00:14:19,745 --> 00:14:22,111
- Tippy!
- Hawk.

260
00:14:22,181 --> 00:14:26,015
What a hell of a trip we had.
We left the carrier this morning.

261
00:14:26,084 --> 00:14:28,518
The chopper was forced
down at, uh, Taejon.

262
00:14:28,587 --> 00:14:31,886
Then we got a cattle train to Ansong.
Tracks were shelled.

263
00:14:31,957 --> 00:14:35,825
Then we had to walk for 10 miles
till a jeep picked us up. But we made it.

264
00:14:35,894 --> 00:14:38,226
Well, what's
the emergency?

265
00:14:38,297 --> 00:14:40,629
Tippy, this is B.J. Hunnicutt.
Uh, B.J., Tippy Brooks.

266
00:14:40,699 --> 00:14:41,723
- Hi.
- How ya doin'?

267
00:14:41,800 --> 00:14:42,892
- We made it.
- Terrific.

268
00:14:42,968 --> 00:14:46,062
- What's the emergency, huh?
- Uh, you tell him.

269
00:14:46,138 --> 00:14:49,232
[Chuckles]
He's your friend.

270
00:14:51,143 --> 00:14:54,909
Tippy, I really didn't think you'd come
all the way out here.

271
00:14:54,980 --> 00:14:57,915
L-I just needed a five-letter
Yiddish word for bedbug.

272
00:15:01,286 --> 00:15:03,777
- What?
- I'm sorry.

273
00:15:03,856 --> 00:15:08,020
You're sorry?
What am I gonna tell Admiral Cox?

274
00:15:08,093 --> 00:15:11,153
Oh, he'll hang me
from the highest, uh...

275
00:15:11,230 --> 00:15:13,994
Um, whatchamacallit...
Uh, seven letters. Starts with "Y."

276
00:15:14,066 --> 00:15:16,432
- "Yardarm."
- Th-Thanks.

277
00:15:16,502 --> 00:15:20,438
Yeah. Look, sit down.
I know you're in a big jam, but first things first.

278
00:15:20,506 --> 00:15:22,440
Do you know
the word? Bedbug?

279
00:15:22,508 --> 00:15:24,442
- Bedbug.
- Five letters.

280
00:15:24,510 --> 00:15:26,444
- Five letters.
- [B.J.] Yiddish.

281
00:15:26,512 --> 00:15:28,446
Yiddish.

282
00:15:28,514 --> 00:15:31,074
- Hawkeye, will you stop?
- I thought as long as you were here.

283
00:15:31,149 --> 00:15:33,310
Look, we really
figured you'd <i>call</i> back.

284
00:15:33,385 --> 00:15:35,353
You guys have really
got me up the creek!

285
00:15:35,420 --> 00:15:37,547
The admiral thinks we're here
for a medical emergency.

286
00:15:37,623 --> 00:15:39,648
- What'll I tell him?
- I could hold my breath.

287
00:15:39,725 --> 00:15:42,455
- We could say it's a case of blue face.
- You'd die.

288
00:15:42,528 --> 00:15:45,588
Right now, a far, far better thing
than me being busted to J.G.

289
00:15:45,664 --> 00:15:48,963
J.G.? They'll bust you
to John Garfield?

290
00:15:51,103 --> 00:15:55,267
You sure surprised me when you
walked in there, Admiral.
Caught me with my guard down.

291
00:15:55,340 --> 00:15:58,070
The call of nature beckons to everybody.
Both army and navy.

292
00:15:58,143 --> 00:16:00,441
- And the marines.
- I'm not too sure about them.

293
00:16:00,512 --> 00:16:02,173
- Coffee?
- Oh, fine.

294
00:16:02,247 --> 00:16:04,772
- Cox. Cox. Is that with an "X"?
- Yes.

295
00:16:04,850 --> 00:16:07,546
That story you told me about gettin' here
is a real rouser.

296
00:16:07,619 --> 00:16:09,553
It's a wonder you weren't killed.

297
00:16:09,621 --> 00:16:13,148
Not that I'm not glad to see ya,
but I can't help wondering why you're here.

298
00:16:13,225 --> 00:16:16,524
I was visiting the <i>Essex</i>
when your emergency call came in.
I've always believed that...

299
00:16:16,595 --> 00:16:19,792
- one branch has to come
to the aid of the other.
- Uh, right.

300
00:16:19,865 --> 00:16:22,834
Now, Admiral, just go in the Mess Tent here.
Order anything you want.

301
00:16:22,901 --> 00:16:27,201
- I wanna check on this emergency.
- Good. I haven't had a bite
since I left the carrier.

302
00:16:27,272 --> 00:16:30,207
- Specialty tonight was Egyptian sauerkraut.
- Egyptian?

303
00:16:30,275 --> 00:16:32,709
- Part of their U.N. Contribution.
- Oh, I see.

304
00:16:32,778 --> 00:16:34,973
We sent back the camels.

305
00:16:37,482 --> 00:16:40,508
- It's all a misunderstanding.
- Getting an admiral here
for a crossword puzzle?

306
00:16:40,586 --> 00:16:42,747
- You guys are one for the book.
- I'm sorry.

307
00:16:42,821 --> 00:16:44,880
- He's sorry.
- You were sorry when...

308
00:16:44,957 --> 00:16:47,152
you gave Major Burns
a chocolate-coated lizard.

309
00:16:47,225 --> 00:16:50,752
- It was Easter.
- Now you've put your buddy's butt in a sling?

310
00:16:50,829 --> 00:16:52,763
What are we gonna
tell the admiral?

311
00:16:52,831 --> 00:16:56,597
We gotta think of something
legitimate. He's no dummy.
He can see through a bulkhead.

312
00:16:56,668 --> 00:16:59,228
Maybe we could run him through post-op,
see what turns up there.

313
00:16:59,304 --> 00:17:03,331
Okay. He's bound to find problems
he's never seen on a nice, clean ship.

314
00:17:03,408 --> 00:17:06,104
Filth, do your stuff.

315
00:17:06,178 --> 00:17:09,147
- Hey, don't worry about it.
- We're in trouble all the time.

316
00:17:14,353 --> 00:17:16,583
- Say good-bye, Dr. Pierce.
- So long, Soo Ling.

317
00:17:16,655 --> 00:17:18,782
- Prisoner exchange.
- Thirty of theirs for 40 of ours.

318
00:17:18,857 --> 00:17:21,690
- It's a sale.
- Did you bring us here just to show us that?

319
00:17:21,760 --> 00:17:23,728
- Uh, no, no, Admiral.
- Of course not.

320
00:17:23,795 --> 00:17:26,696
Here's a difficult case.
Uh, Pierce?

321
00:17:26,765 --> 00:17:30,292
Thank you, Colonel. Following routine
extraction of shrapnel from the leg...

322
00:17:30,369 --> 00:17:32,997
this patient displayed
unusual dehydration.

323
00:17:33,071 --> 00:17:35,562
An insatiable need
for liquids.

324
00:17:35,641 --> 00:17:38,269
- Like a drink, soldier?
- No, thank you. I'm not thirsty.

325
00:17:40,412 --> 00:17:42,642
- I can't thank you enough, Admiral.
- It's a miracle.

326
00:17:42,714 --> 00:17:45,274
- Can we get on with this?
- Yeah, let's get on with this.

327
00:17:45,350 --> 00:17:49,684
- Okay, let's get on with this.
- Admiral, this is Corporal Klinger.

328
00:17:53,358 --> 00:17:55,553
- What is it, soldier?
- [Mutters]

329
00:17:55,627 --> 00:17:57,561
Huh?

330
00:17:57,629 --> 00:18:00,757
- Klinger!
- Sorry. I usually don't kiss on the first date.

331
00:18:00,832 --> 00:18:04,097
- What kind of a place are you running here?
- This case is very unusual.

332
00:18:04,169 --> 00:18:07,138
- This case has a screw loose.
- Close. Baker, get us Klinger's X ray.

333
00:18:07,205 --> 00:18:10,038
Admiral, if you can't send me home,
can I transfer to the navy?

334
00:18:10,108 --> 00:18:13,407
Look at that sonar.
He could smell a sub at 30 fathoms.

335
00:18:16,014 --> 00:18:18,710
Nuts, bolts, knobs?
This guy's full of machinery.

336
00:18:18,784 --> 00:18:22,413
- He was trying to eat a jeep.
- Eat a jeep? He shouldn't
even be in the service!

337
00:18:22,487 --> 00:18:25,513
- I love you!
- Aah!

338
00:18:25,590 --> 00:18:28,184
Only take me a minute
to pack my makeup kit and rollers.

339
00:18:28,260 --> 00:18:31,093
Stop it! You've got
no emergency here, Potter.

340
00:18:31,163 --> 00:18:34,894
We have wasted valuable time!
Now I am gonna see there's an investigation!

341
00:18:34,966 --> 00:18:38,902
Come on, Brooks.
Let's get out of this loony bin.

342
00:18:38,970 --> 00:18:42,462
There's been a terrible accident!
Civilians! They're all burned!

343
00:18:42,541 --> 00:18:45,669
<i>[Potter] Crank up the O.R. Generator!</i>
<i>We'll need plenty of plasma.</i>

344
00:18:49,281 --> 00:18:51,215
- Oh, watch out. Kellye!
- Careful now.

345
00:18:51,283 --> 00:18:53,012
Get 'em inside.
Easy.

346
00:18:53,085 --> 00:18:55,781
We have to bring them
in pre-op and treat 'em in O.R.

347
00:18:55,854 --> 00:18:59,346
<i>[Margaret]</i>
<i>Father Mulcahy!</i>

348
00:18:59,424 --> 00:19:02,052
<i>Easy. Get her</i>
<i>into pre-op. Move it.</i>

349
00:19:02,127 --> 00:19:05,426
- [Moaning]
- Father, straight into O.R.

350
00:19:05,497 --> 00:19:07,658
- Napalm?
- No, sir. Gasoline.

351
00:19:07,733 --> 00:19:09,724
- All right, get him into O.R.
- Let's go.

352
00:19:09,801 --> 00:19:12,736
- Easy. Go easy now.
- What a mess!

353
00:19:12,804 --> 00:19:15,398
- There's caps and masks
in the scrub room, Tippy.
- Right.

354
00:19:15,474 --> 00:19:17,772
- We've got a baby here!
- [Klinger] Okay, I'll help.

355
00:19:17,843 --> 00:19:20,141
- Okay.
- Easy. Easy now.

356
00:19:20,212 --> 00:19:22,146
- You got her?
- Yep.

357
00:19:22,214 --> 00:19:24,614
- You a corpsman?
- The best in the business, dad.

358
00:19:24,683 --> 00:19:26,913
An army fuel truck
turned over in a ditch.

359
00:19:26,985 --> 00:19:29,545
- The Koreans were soaking up
the gasoline with rags.
- What for?

360
00:19:29,621 --> 00:19:31,316
- To use in their lamps.
- Wonderful.

361
00:19:31,389 --> 00:19:34,552
You know what happened? When it got dark
they couldn't see what they were doing.

362
00:19:34,626 --> 00:19:36,890
- Some guy lit a match.
- And a few of his friends.

363
00:19:36,962 --> 00:19:38,896
More plasma.

364
00:19:38,964 --> 00:19:40,795
- You got enough morphine?
- We'll get by.

365
00:19:40,866 --> 00:19:42,697
Got one who can't breathe.
Smoke inhalation.

366
00:19:42,768 --> 00:19:44,429
- Bad enough for a tracheotomy?
- Yep.

367
00:19:44,503 --> 00:19:47,165
- You want help?
- I got it.

368
00:19:47,239 --> 00:19:51,767
I can't fix your arm until you give me the kid.
I insist you give me the kid!

369
00:19:51,843 --> 00:19:54,175
- [Speaking Korean]
- Well, if you can't speak English...

370
00:19:54,246 --> 00:19:56,510
why don't you go back
where you came from?

371
00:19:56,581 --> 00:19:59,311
- Major Burns, let me help.
- It's-It's a waste of time, Father!

372
00:19:59,384 --> 00:20:01,944
[Korean]

373
00:20:04,055 --> 00:20:06,649
- They're heathen.
- We're all God's children.

374
00:20:06,725 --> 00:20:11,594
- Oh, really?
- It's just that some of us are
more childish than others.

375
00:20:12,864 --> 00:20:15,230
- Margaret, 500 of Ringer's lactate.
- Yes, Doctor.

376
00:20:15,300 --> 00:20:18,326
<i>[B.J.]</i>
<i>Klinger, post-op.</i>

377
00:20:18,403 --> 00:20:20,337
- [Potter] Klinger.
- Sir?

378
00:20:20,405 --> 00:20:22,339
Your nose slipped out
of its bra.

379
00:20:22,407 --> 00:20:25,433
- Sorry, ladies.
- Give ya a hand, Colonel?

380
00:20:25,510 --> 00:20:27,102
- Pierce?
- Yes, Admiral?

381
00:20:27,179 --> 00:20:30,205
I've debrided the burn and applied
the dressing. Anything more I can do?

382
00:20:30,282 --> 00:20:32,546
Not a thing. Unless you want
to sign up for a year.

383
00:20:32,617 --> 00:20:34,510
No, thanks.
You guys work too hard.

384
00:20:34,643 --> 00:20:38,238
#<i>#[Radio]</i>

385
00:20:38,314 --> 00:20:42,546
Seven hours in surgery.
And atop of Egyptian sauerkraut.

386
00:20:42,618 --> 00:20:45,109
Is that coffee?

387
00:20:45,187 --> 00:20:47,451
Powdered milk,
but she won't take it.

388
00:20:47,523 --> 00:20:49,457
<i>[Hawkeye]</i>
<i>That kid wasn't born yesterday.</i>

389
00:20:49,525 --> 00:20:52,585
- <i>[Woman On Radio] This is Seoul City Sue.</i>
- Time for the commercial.

390
00:20:52,661 --> 00:20:56,188
<i>I have a special message</i>
<i>for the members of MASH 4077.</i>

391
00:20:56,265 --> 00:20:58,199
- [Cheering]
- We're on the radio.

392
00:20:58,267 --> 00:21:01,031
<i>One of the prisoners you returned</i>
<i>has had head surgery...</i>

393
00:21:01,103 --> 00:21:03,162
<i>for the purpose</i>
<i>of inhuman experiments.</i>

394
00:21:03,239 --> 00:21:05,799
<i>We brand Dr. Hawkeye Pierce</i>
<i>a war criminal.</i>

395
00:21:05,875 --> 00:21:08,400
- A war criminal?
- All I did was stitch up that guy's scalp.

396
00:21:08,477 --> 00:21:10,411
Was I supposed
to let him bleed to death?

397
00:21:10,479 --> 00:21:14,040
- Turn the other cheek, Hawkeye.
- Both cheeks are already sore.

398
00:21:14,116 --> 00:21:17,085
That dame lies as much as
my sister-in-law, Bertha.

399
00:21:17,153 --> 00:21:21,112
You know, that really roasts
my butt. Why don't we put out
some propaganda of our own?

400
00:21:21,190 --> 00:21:23,750
- <i>[Brooks] Like what, Admiral?</i>
- Like those burn victims.

401
00:21:23,826 --> 00:21:27,592
Why don't we say they were firebombed by
the enemy because they cooperated with us?

402
00:21:27,663 --> 00:21:30,723
- Why should we say that?
- Because it's a very effective weapon, Pierce.

403
00:21:30,799 --> 00:21:33,768
Every time they put out something,
we should put out something worse.

404
00:21:33,836 --> 00:21:35,929
They lie and then we lie.
Where does it end?

405
00:21:36,005 --> 00:21:38,974
Oh, maybe you're right.
But it still steams me.

406
00:21:39,041 --> 00:21:41,908
It steams me too,
but it's gotta stop somewhere.

407
00:21:41,977 --> 00:21:46,073
She simply won't take powdered milk.
She needs fresh. I wish we had a goat.

408
00:21:46,148 --> 00:21:48,810
Let me try, Father.

409
00:21:48,884 --> 00:21:51,853
Hi. Can I see you
for a little bit?

410
00:21:51,921 --> 00:21:54,219
Let me see you
for a little bit, huh?

411
00:21:55,991 --> 00:21:58,152
Get a little of this stuff.

412
00:21:58,227 --> 00:22:01,628
[Imitating Goat Bleating]

413
00:22:04,166 --> 00:22:07,567
You want the cup?
[Bleating]

414
00:22:09,071 --> 00:22:11,801
[Bleating]

415
00:22:11,874 --> 00:22:14,809
<i>[Mulcahy]</i>
<i>She's taking the milk.</i>

416
00:22:14,877 --> 00:22:18,335
Now that's propaganda.

417
00:22:21,250 --> 00:22:24,344
I can't tell you how grateful
I am for the way you two pitched in.

418
00:22:24,420 --> 00:22:27,617
- Uh, glad we could help.
- Can he drive all right?

419
00:22:27,690 --> 00:22:30,853
Sure. That's his
driving hat.

420
00:22:30,926 --> 00:22:34,123
One more thing. Pierce, you obviously
didn't need us when you called.

421
00:22:34,196 --> 00:22:36,460
Why did you
get us up here?

422
00:22:36,532 --> 00:22:38,591
Well, I'm sorry, Admiral.
It was a misunderstanding.

423
00:22:38,667 --> 00:22:40,601
We needed help
with a crossword puzzle.

424
00:22:40,669 --> 00:22:42,796
A crossword puzzle?

425
00:22:42,871 --> 00:22:45,465
We were stuck. A five-letter
Yiddish word for bedbug.

426
00:22:45,541 --> 00:22:47,702
I don't believe it.

427
00:22:47,776 --> 00:22:51,143
You dragged us all the way up here
just to get the word <i>"vont</i>z<i>"?</i>

428
00:22:51,213 --> 00:22:53,147
<i>Vont</i>z<i>!</i>

429
00:22:53,215 --> 00:22:56,150
- <i>Vont</i>z<i>!</i>
- Beej, it's <i>vont</i>z<i>!</i>

430
00:22:56,218 --> 00:22:58,880
Good luck, Admiral.

431
00:22:58,954 --> 00:23:02,185
Now look, we've got plenty of time.
There's no need to speed.

432
00:23:02,258 --> 00:23:04,283
Aye, aye, sir.

433
00:23:10,532 --> 00:23:13,558
And, Klinger, no kissing!

434
00:23:16,405 --> 00:23:19,340
[Laughing]
I got 14 B.B.'s in the holes.

435
00:23:19,408 --> 00:23:21,342
Now only one more to go.

436
00:23:21,410 --> 00:23:24,243
- Want some help with that?
- I can manage by myself, thank you.

437
00:23:24,313 --> 00:23:27,441
- You're welcome.
- You're spending a lot of time
and energy on that fool thing.

438
00:23:27,516 --> 00:23:30,144
